"{\"uid\": \"si.com-gail-devers-q-a-it-s-show-out-time-for-sha-carri-richardson-team-usa-at-paris-olympics-100-meters\", \"text\": \"Gail Devers\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s story is too remarkable to fit into a single introductory paragraph. The fastest version: elite Olympian comes down with unknown health condition, struggles at the 1988 Seoul Games, drops 79 pounds, nearly loses a foot; is diagnosed with Graves\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 disease, embarks on stunning comeback, competes in two more Olympics (five total), wins three gold medals; becomes the subject of a TV movie,Run For the Dream:The Gail Devers Story.  Sha\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Carri Richardson is favored to win the 100 meters Saturday. The last American woman to win the 100 meters at the Olympics? Gail Devers, at the 1996 Atlanta Games. SI spoke with Devers about the 100-meter dash, Team USA and what she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s up to now, at 53.  (This interview has been edited for length and clarity.)  Gail Devers:Man, that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s like 28 years ago. That was not my concern at all. I volunteer as a coach at a local high school. The kids are texting about all these things. Like,Gail,someone just broke your 24-year-old Olympic record[in the 100-meter hurdles]. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m like,I didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t know I had it,so OK! It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the same thing with bringing back the gold. I think this year, more than any other, we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve sent a great team to Paris. If this isthe year, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s going to be a joyous time.  GD:The U.S. team is one of the hardest teams to make. The best example is the 100-meter hurdles final [at U.S. trials] alone. Our fourth- and fifth-place runners [Nia Ali and Tonea Marshall, respectively, who both ran season-best times] could make the Olympic final. And they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re sitting at home.  GD:It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s hard to pick. Let\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s go back to trials and see who made the team. First of all, they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re young. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s their first Olympic games. That makes you hungry. And the three that made the team [Richardson, Melissa Jefferson and Twanisha Terry] are from the same camp. They have the same coach [Dennis Mitchell]. Now, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s show-out time. If you watch Sha\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Carri, all of them, practice, they all show up. She\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s certainly capable. Now, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s forget about those five rings. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the same thing we do every day, on the track\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094execute what you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve been taught.  GD:Everything was different\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094translating, transportation, hotels, training. But that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s what progress is. You want each generation to get better and better. Now, we have the Diamond League. Back then, we didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t have meets in the states. So you had to go to Europe. We\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re all riding the bus together, riding on planes together, riding on the trains.  GD:That was when I should have been on top of the world. And I was, for a moment, because I had broken the American record for the 100-meter hurdles, in college. The statisticians are saying,If she just runs what she ran a couple months,we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re gonna have a medal. And then I got to the Games and the bottom fell out. I ran slower than I ever ran. There was a problem. It took three years before I was ever diagnosed. I was constantly losing weight, tired all the time, couldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t sleep. I had problems with my eyes, bulging eye pain. As an athlete, you know your body, and you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re like,Something\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not right. Finally, I got diagnosed. Grave\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s disease is an auto-immune disease that causes hyper-thyroidism. Two years later, I came back, and I won my first Olympic gold medal. And then the other shoe dropped.  GD:I was still having problems, throughout that whole ordeal, with my eyes. Running over hurdles, everything was blurry. I could never see the hurdles clearly. I had learned to negotiate going over those hurdles. What the rhythm is. That there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s eight steps from the blocks to the first hurdle. That there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s three steps in between. Five steps off the last hurdle to the finish line. But I don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t want to run in rhythm. Because if I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m running in rhythm, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m running like everybody else. I want to sprint and take those hurdles. I thought it was the residual effect of the Grave\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s. But three decades later, I was having problems. I stopped driving at night. The lights coming at me were blinding. After three decades, I found out my eye problems were from a separate-but-related condition called Thyroid Eye Disease.I call him TED, because if somebody\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s been living with you for 30 years, he deserves a name. I had to become that voice, hope, advocate for other people.  GD:Take care of your body\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and I mean beyond getting ready for races. Go to doctors. Find a TED specialist. Think long-term. Go and find a specialist and ask for a comprehensive exam. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 Don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t take the marathon route with healthcare. If you know better, do better. I hope my story gives people belief and hope. When [doctors considered amputating her foot], I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m like,OK,you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re going to take my foot.You\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re not going to take my joy.  GD:My dad always said I was a force to be reckoned with. So we have the Gale Force Foundation [also listed online as the Gail Devers Foundation, Inc.]. If I look back at my life, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m a teacher. Now, the world is my classroom.  GD:That\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the plan.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Greg Bishop is a senior writer for Sports Illustrated who has covered every kind of sport and every major event across six continents for more than two decades. He previously worked for The Seattle Times and The New York Times. He is the co-author of two books: Jim Gray\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s memoir, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTalking to GOATs\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d; and Laurent Duvernay Tardif\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cRed Zone\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d. Bishop has written for Showtime Sports, Prime Video and DAZN, and has been nominated for eight sports Emmys, winning two, both for production. He has completed more than a dozen documentary film projects, with a wide range of duties. Bishop, who graduated from the Newhouse School at Syracuse University, is based in Seattle.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"